    "Command line interfaces\n",
    "=======================\n",
    "\n",
    "If you are viewing this page on a computer, you are probably using a point-and-click [Graphical User Interface](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_user_interface) (GUI, pronounced *GOO-ee*). GUI's became mainstream with the rise of personal computers in the 1980s, but prior to that, programmers did most of their work using text commands on a Command Line Interface (CLI). Today, CLIs are alive and well, but due to their steep learning curve they tend to be used mostly by seasoned programmers and developers or those with a computer science background. \n",
    "\n",
    "**You don't need to know how to use the command line in order to learn a programming language like Python.** \n",
    "\n",
    "That said, intermediates like myself are waking up to the power and flexibility that a bit of command line knowledge affords. Yes, the learning curve is steep, but you can get by knowing only a few commands. And..."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6a708e9c-beae-4696-8386-2c6a61bb63cd",

   "source": [
    "__IMPORTANT NOTE__\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a complete command line tutorial but a 'first-contact' command line experience walkthrough. If you already know your way around the command line and you just want to learn how to have your fortune told by a rainbow cow, skip to the end.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you are serious about learning the command line, here are some excellent resources:\n",
    " \n",
    "  - [Bash beginners guide](https://tldp.org/LDP/Bash-Beginners-Guide/html/index.html)\n",
    "  - [Advanced Bash scripting guide](https://tldp.org/LDP/abs/html/)\n",
    "  - [Learn the Linux command line](https://linuxcommand.org/)\n",
    "  - [Linux survival](https://linuxsurvival.com/)\n",
    "  - [A to Z of the Linux command line](https://ss64.com/bash/)\n",
    "  - [Top websites and books to transform you into a Linux command line hero](https://www.makeuseof.com/tag/top-3-sites-to-help-you-become-a-linux-command-line-master/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed:+Makeuseof+(MakeUseOf.com))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "becf8f0e-7733-4634-b9df-32d4461d3a5e",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "Basics\n",
    "------\n",
    "\n",
    "To unlock the power of the command line you will need to launch a terminal, sometimes referred to as a shell, or even less appropriately, a console. To avoid confusion, a terminal is a program that provides a textual input and output environment, a shell is a program that runs in the background and exposes the operating system's services at the command line interface, and a console typically implies a physical object (e.g., a gaming console or a control panel). Nevertheless, these words are often used interchangeably for something that looks like this:\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"_static/terminal_img.png\" alt=\"Image of terminal application\" width=\"800\"/>\n",
    "\n",
    "Shown above is an instance of the macOS Terminal.app after having entered a few simple commands. The terminal is running a [Z shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z_shell) (`zsh`) in the background, which is now the default shell on macOS. However, there are many different types of shell&mdash;it all depends on which operating system you are using and whether you have chosen one specifically. Windows has the [Command shell](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/windows-commands) and [PowerShell](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/scripting/overview?view=powershell-7.3), which we will not be focusing on here. [Unix-like operating systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like) such as [Ubuntu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ubuntu) and [macOS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacOS) support even more types of shell. These include:\n",
    "\n",
    "  - [C shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_shell) (`csh`)\n",
    "  - [Bourne shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bourne_shell) (`sh`)\n",
    "  - [GNU-Bourne-Again shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bash_(Unix_shell)) (`bash`)\n",
    "  - [KornShell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KornShell) (`ksh`)\n",
    "  - [Tee-see-shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tcsh) (`tcsh`)\n",
    "  - [Debian-Almquist-shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almquist_shell#dash) (`dash`)\n",
    "  - [Friendly-interactive-shell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_(Unix_shell)) (`fish`)\n",
    "\n",
    "Admittedly, this is confusing, but you need not despair. Unix shells all function in a very similar way at a fundamental level, and you should be able to follow this tutorial using any non-Windows shell environment. Most likely this will be `bash` or `zsh`.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you want to complete this tutorial on a Windows machine and you are running Windows 10 or above, you can install the [Windows Subsytem for Linux](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install). In brief (but do your own research first), enter `wsl --install` in a PowerShell, wait for the installation to complete, restart your computer, go to the Microsoft Store, search 'Linux', install a Linux distribution (e.g., Ubuntu), and you can then click on the shortcut for whichever distribution you just installed and launch the terminal application.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4c83f887-d284-4114-bf84-81fb769df219",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Start a terminal\n",
    "----------------\n",
    "\n",
    "The first step to learning the command line is launching a terminal application. On macOS, it's called Terminal.app and you you can find it in the Applications folder, search for it using `Cmd-Space`, or look for it in the Launchpad. On Linux, depending on your distribution, it could be called Terminal, Terminal Emulator, Terminator, or something like that. Either way, look for an application that sounds like terminal.\n",
    "\n",
    "After launching the terminal application, type `echo $SHELL` and press `Enter` to find out what shell program you are running. This will probably be `bash` or `zsh`. \n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"_static/terminal_shell.png\" alt=\"Image of terminal application\" width=\"800\"/>\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fb8a359d-3ea7-41ca-ab80-5991d87b14d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First shell commands\n",
    "--------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "As noted previously, knowing just a few commands is enough to get by at the command line. The table below displays some of the most ubiquitous shell commands, and if you can learn how to use these you will be off to a very good start. \n",
    "\n",
    "| Command    | Description                                                                         |\n",
    "|:-----------|:------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| `pwd`      | Show the path of the current working directory                                      |\n",
    "| `ls`       | LiSt files and directories in current directory                                     |\n",
    "| `cd`       | Change directory                                                                    |\n",
    "| `touch`    | Create a new file                                                                   |\n",
    "| `mkdir`    | Create a new directory                                                              |\n",
    "| `rm`       | Remove a file or directory                                                          |\n",
    "| `cp`       | Copy a file or directory                                                            |\n",
    "| `mv`       | Move or rename a file or directory                                                  |\n",
    "| `echo`     | Print text to the standard output                                                   |\n",
    "| `cat`      | Concatenate / display files                                                         |\n",
    "| `more`     | Display contents of a file, starting at the top and letting the user scroll down.   |\n",
    "| `less`     | Display contents of a file in an even more interactive way.                         |\n",
    "| `head`     | Display the first part of a file.                                                   |\n",
    "| `tail`     | Display the last part of a file.                                                    |\n",
    "| `man`      | Display documentation about a command                                               |\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's dive in. Type each of the following commands (highlighted in gray) in order and then press `Enter`. \n",
    "\n",
    "  1. `pwd` - Print out the path of the current working directory (the folder that you are currently inside), which is likely to be your home folder\n",
    "  2. `mkdir tutorial` - Make a new directory for this tutorial\n",
    "  3. `cd tutorial` - Change to the tutorial directory that you just created\n",
    "  4. `pwd` - Confirm that you are now inside the new tutorial directory\n",
    "  5. `touch README.txt` - Create an empty text file called `README.txt`\n",
    "  6. `echo \"This folder contains tutorial stuff.\" >> README.txt` - Add some text to `README.txt`\n",
    "  7. `cat README.txt` - Display the text from `README.txt`\n",
    "  8. `touch file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt` - Create some empty text files\n",
    "  9. `ls` - List the contents of the current working directory\n",
    "  10. `echo \"Shall I compare thee to a summer's day?\" >> file1.txt` - Add some text to the new files\n",
    "  11. `echo \"Thou art more lovely and more temperate.\" >> file2.txt`\n",
    "  12. `echo \"Rough winds do shake the darling buds of May,\" >> file3.txt` \n",
    "  13. `echo \"And summer's lease hath all too short a date.\" >> file4.txt`\n",
    "  14. `cat file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt` - Concatenate and print the lines from each file\n",
    "  15. `mkdir poetry` - Make a new directory called poetry\n",
    "  16. `cat file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt >> ./poetry/sonnet18.txt` - Concatenate the lines and save as a new file in poetry\n",
    "  17. `rm file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt` - Remove (delete) these files\n",
    "  18. `cd poetry` - Change to new poetry folder\n",
    "  19. `say -f sonnet18.txt` - Speak the poem aloud (may only work on macOS)\n",
    "\n",
    "When you have finished, your terminal should look something like this.\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"_static/terminal_cmds_1.png\" alt=\"Image of terminal application\" width=\"800\"/>\n",
    "\n",
    "In this little exercise, you used common shell commands to make directories and to create and process some text files. Now it is time to dive deeper and learn more about each of these commands using `man`. \n",
    "\n",
    "First, type `man pwd` to display the manual pages for the `pwd` command. When you are finished reading, press `q` to exit the manual pages. Repeat this process for all of the commands used above.\n",
    "\n",
    "You will see that most commands have different options that can be used to alter how the command works. Man pages are often boring and abstruse, but ultimately they contain all of the information you need to use a command correctly. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9a04058a-bab0-481e-b57e-7fc0e557fd07",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`fortune | cowsay | lolcat`\n",
    "---------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a way to make the command line fun. \n",
    "\n",
    "`fortuen`, `cowsay` and `lolcat` are shell programs that can work together as follows.\n"
   ]

   "source": [
    "Installation\n",
    "------------\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### macOS\n",
    "\n",
    "The easiest way to complete installation on macOS is via the [Homebrew](https://brew.sh/) package manager. To install Homebrew, open a terminal and enter the following command:\n",
    "\n",
    "```bash\n",
    "/bin/bash -c \"$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)\"\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "When the installation is complete, you can then type the following command to install the packages:\n",
    "\n",
    "```bash\n",
    "brew install fortune cowsay lolcat\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

    "Putting it all together\n",
    "-----------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "A cool thing about these packages is that the output of one can be 'piped' to another. This is achieved using the `|` operator. This effectively means we can have our fortune told by a rainbow colored cow. It may not be to everyone's taste, but personally I like to see this every time I start up the command line."
   ]

   "source": [
    "cowfiles = [c.split(' ') for c in cowfiles[1:]]  # First line is not an option\n",
    "cowfiles = [c for sublist in cowfiles for c in sublist]  # Flatten the list\n",
    "print(cowfiles, '\\n')  # This is our list of cowfiles"
   ]
